description: Messier 2 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 37,200 light-years away in the constellation Aquarius. It is one of the largest known globular clusters containing about 150,000 stars. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more

Messier 3 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 32,600 light-years away in the constellation of Canes Venatici. This cluster is one of the largest and brightest containing an estimated 500,000 stars. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more

Messier 5 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 23,800 light-years away in the constellation Serpens. It is one of the oldest globulars associated with the Milky Way galaxy and contains more than 100,000 stars. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more

Messier 13 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 22,800 light-years away in the constellation Hercules and is composed of several hundred thousand stars. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more

Messier 15 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 33,300 light-years away in the constellation Pegasus. M15 contains over 100,000 stars and is one of the most densely packed globulars known in the Milky Way galaxy. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more

Messier 53 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 60,000 light-years away in the constellation Coma Berenices and is one of the more outlying globular clusters associated with the Milky Way galaxy. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
Messier 92 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 26,400 light-years away in the constellation Hercules. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
NGC 2419 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 268,400 light-years away in the constellation Lynx. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
NGC 5053 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 52,800 light-years away in the constellation Coma Berenices. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
NGC 5466 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 54,100 light-years away in the constellation Bootes. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
NGC 6535 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 22,200 light-years away in the constellation Serpens. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
NGC 6934 is a globular cluster of stars approximately 49,600 light-years away in the constellation Delphinus. Best seen in the optical SDSS9 sky. Read more
